Red sprites are rare electrical discharges that occur high above thunderstorms, typically between 40–80 km in altitude. Unlike regular lightning, which strikes downward, red sprites shoot upward into the upper atmosphere, producing an eerie red glow as nitrogen reacts with the electrical energy — often resembling fireworks or glowing jellyfish.

As reported by APT, the red sprites were captured by Chinese astrophotographer Dong Shuchang who recorded them in breathtaking slow motion using high-speed camera technology

VC- @shuchang_dong 
#NewsWithTN 
[ Red sprites, viral]

For the past five years, 69-year-old Dutch national Ellis Hubertina Spaanderman—known as the "Mother of Dal"—has been tirelessly working to clean plastic pollution from Kashmir’s iconic Dal Lake. Often seen collecting discarded bags and bottles, her selfless efforts have inspired many and sparked conversations on environmental responsibility. Her mission highlights the urgent need to protect the region’s natural beauty.

This striking “tsunami cloud,” or roll cloud, forms when cool sea air collides with warm, moist air, creating a long, tube-shaped cloud that rolls across the sky. It was seen in coastal towns like Figueira da Foz, Póvoa de Varzim, and Vila do Conde.

Despite its dramatic appearance, the cloud was completely harmless — a breathtaking reminder of nature’s artistry.

When a pod of dolphins tore through South Bay’s glowing waters, it didn’t look real. Each movement lit the ocean in electric blue, like the sea had come alive.

The science? It’s called bioluminescence—a glow triggered when tiny plankton (dinoflagellates) are disturbed, sparking a chemical reaction that turns motion into light.

Seen from California to the Arabian Sea, this surreal phenomenon is harmless to marine life and often marks nutrient-rich, thriving waters.

🎥: @joshg_photos

His intelligence saved thousands of lives, but he died in silence—buried behind prison walls, forgotten by the country he served.

Nagendra Prabu, a choreographer and tourist guide from Tamil Nadu, has gone viral for his unique approach to showcasing Indian classical dance. Using mudras, expressions, and storytelling, he transforms heritage tours into engaging cultural performances. His captivating style has earned widespread praise on social media, with many hailing him as a true cultural ambassador who is redefining the way India’s rich traditions are shared with the world.

Daniel Gutiérrez, mayor of San Pedro Huamelula in Mexico, took part in a symbolic wedding with a crocodile as part of a 230-year-old Indigenous ritual. Rooted in the traditions of southern Mexico, the ceremony represents the union of two Indigenous groups and is believed to bring good harvests and abundant fish. The crocodile is honoured and dressed in a bridal gown as part of the festivities.

[Mexico,  crocodile, viral]
#NewsWithTN

In Bihar’s Sheikhpura district, a police officer allegedly assaulted an e-rickshaw driver, Praduman Kumar, after asking his caste. The incident occurred in Mehus village when Kumar was stopped, abused, and later beaten with a lathi by Praveen Chandra Diwakar, the Mehus police station in-charge. Kumar was reportedly forced to lick the officer’s spit after revealing his caste. The driver suffered severe injuries and claimed he was falsely accused and further assaulted at the police station.

[Bihar, caste, police]
